File: platform/mcp-server/src/server-node.ts, lines 64-73.

Current code:
```
const nodeStream = Readable.fromWeb(body as unknown as NodeReadableStream);
nodeStream.pipe(res);
nodeStream.on('error', err => {
  log.warn('Response stream error:', err);
  if (!res.headersSent) {
    res.writeHead(500);
  }
  res.end();
});
res.on('close', () => nodeStream.destroy());
```

The fix should change the error handler to:
1. If headers have NOT been sent: keep existing behavior (writeHead 500, res.end())
2. If headers HAVE been sent (SSE stream already started): call res.destroy() instead of res.end(), so the TCP connection drops and the MCP client sees a transport error rather than a valid-but-truncated SSE stream
3. Always call nodeStream.destroy() in the error handler to stop the source stream

This is the Node.js HTTP adapter used for MCP Streamable HTTP transport. SSE responses hold the connection open while tool dispatches run (up to 30s). A mid-stream error that cleanly ends the response makes it look like a normal end-of-stream to the client.

File: platform/mcp-server/src/resolver.ts, lines 155-176.

Current code uses spawnSync:
```
const getGlobalNodeModulesPaths = (): string[] => {
  const cached = getCachedGlobalPaths();
  if (cached !== null) return cached;
  const paths: string[] = [];
  try {
    const result = spawnSync(platformExec('npm'), ['root', '-g'], { stdio: ['ignore', 'pipe', 'pipe'] });
    if (!result.error && result.status === 0) {
      const npmPath = result.stdout.toString().trim();
      if (npmPath.length > 0) paths.push(npmPath);
    }
  } catch (e) {
    log.debug(`npm root -g failed: ${toErrorMessage(e)}`);
  }
  if (paths.length > 0) setCachedGlobalPaths(paths);
  return paths;
};
```

